# IECC Automatic Receptacle Control Requirements

---

# 0. Purpose and Scope

This page documents **regulatory requirements governing Automatic Receptacle Control (ARC)** as defined by the International Energy Conservation Code (IECC).

ARC requirements are intended to reduce plug-load energy consumption by ensuring that receptacles serving general equipment loads are automatically de-energized when the associated space is not actively in use.

This page focuses on **what the IECC requires**, not how systems should be designed.

Design approaches and implementation strategies are documented in:

- [[Automatic Receptacle Control]]
- [[ARC Design Playbook]]

---

# 1. Regulatory Definition

## Automatic Receptacle Control (ARC)

Automatic Receptacle Control refers to **the automatic control of receptacle outlets serving plug loads** such that power is removed from those outlets when certain conditions are met.

These conditions typically include:

- vacancy of the space
- time-of-day schedules
- signals from control systems

ARC requirements generally apply to **receptacles serving general plug loads**, not dedicated equipment.

---

# 2. Governing Codes and Standards

The following standards commonly define ARC requirements:

- **IECC (International Energy Conservation Code)**
- **ASHRAE 90.1**

This page focuses specifically on **IECC requirements**.

Local jurisdictions may modify or amend these requirements.

---

# 3. Requirements

---

## 3.1 IECC 2021

### Relevant Code Sections

- IECC 2021 – Section **C405.10** (Automatic Receptacle Control)

---

### Core Requirements

Buildings must include automatic receptacle control for **plug-load receptacles** in certain spaces.

Typical requirements include:

- At least **50% of 125V 15A and 20A receptacles** in applicable spaces must be automatically controlled.
- Controlled receptacles must automatically turn off under defined conditions.
- Controlled receptacles must be **visually identified**.
- Controlled receptacles must restore power upon occupancy or manual override.

---

### Space-Type Trigger Matrix (Typical Applications)

| Space Type | ARC Required | Notes |
|-------------|-------------|------|
| Enclosed Offices | Yes | Typically tied to occupancy sensor control |
| Open Offices | Yes | Often integrated with lighting control zones |
| Conference Rooms | Yes | Usually occupancy sensor or schedule-based |
| Classrooms | Yes | May integrate with lighting control system |
| Break Rooms | Yes | Controlled receptacles often provided at counters |
| Copy / Print Rooms | Yes | Equipment exceptions often apply |
| Corridors | No | Plug loads typically not considered general-purpose |
| Restrooms | No | Receptacles typically dedicated loads |
| Mechanical Rooms | No | Equipment loads exempt |
| Server / IT Rooms | No | Continuous power required |

---

### Exceptions

Receptacles that are **not required to be automatically controlled** typically include:

- Receptacles serving **refrigerators**
- Receptacles serving **vending machines**
- Receptacles serving **information technology equipment**
- Receptacles serving **life safety systems**
- Receptacles serving **equipment requiring continuous power**

---

### Conditions That Trigger the Requirement

ARC requirements typically apply when:

- Spaces contain **general-purpose receptacles**
- Spaces are **regularly occupied**
- Equipment loads are not dedicated or exempt

---

### Allowable Compliance Methods

IECC permits several approaches to ARC implementation:

- Occupancy sensor control
- Time-switch control
- Building automation system scheduling
- Manual override with automatic reset

---

## 3.2 IECC 2024

### Relevant Code Sections

- IECC 2024 – Section **C405.10** (Automatic Receptacle Control)

---

### Core Requirements

IECC 2024 maintains the requirement that **a portion of general-purpose receptacles must be automatically controlled**.

Key elements include:

- At least **50% of applicable receptacles must be automatically controlled**
- Controlled receptacles must automatically shut off when spaces are unoccupied
- Controlled receptacles must be **visually identified**
- Occupant override must be available

---

### Space-Type Trigger Matrix (Typical Applications)

| Space Type | ARC Required | Notes |
|-------------|-------------|------|
| Enclosed Offices | Yes | Frequently implemented using lighting occupancy sensors |
| Open Offices | Yes | Often integrated with lighting control zones |
| Conference Rooms | Yes | Typically occupancy-controlled |
| Classrooms | Yes | May integrate with BAS or lighting systems |
| Break Rooms | Yes | Counter receptacles often partially controlled |
| Copy / Print Rooms | Yes | Dedicated equipment exceptions common |
| Corridors | No | Receptacles typically not general plug loads |
| Restrooms | No | Receptacles generally dedicated loads |
| Mechanical Rooms | No | Equipment loads exempt |
| Server / IT Rooms | No | Continuous power required |

---

### Exceptions

Common exceptions include receptacles serving:

- refrigeration equipment
- information technology equipment
- life safety systems
- equipment with built-in energy management
- equipment requiring continuous power

---

### Conditions That Trigger the Requirement

ARC typically applies when:

- receptacles serve **general plug loads**
- spaces are **regularly occupied**
- receptacles are not dedicated equipment circuits

---

### Allowable Compliance Methods

ARC may be implemented using:

- occupancy sensor control
- time-switch control
- BAS scheduling
- manual override with automatic reset

---

# 4. Interactions with Other Codes

ARC implementation may interact with other codes including:

**NEC**

- branch circuit wiring
- split receptacle wiring
- switching of receptacle circuits

**IBC**

- occupancy classifications affecting space use

**Local Amendments**

- some jurisdictions modify ARC requirements or enforcement practices.

## 4.1 NEC — Switched Receptacles

Automatic Receptacle Control systems often require receptacle circuits to be switched.

This introduces interactions with the **National Electrical Code (NEC)** governing receptacle wiring configurations.

---

### Typical Wiring Configuration

A common ARC implementation uses **split-wired receptacles**, where:

- One half of the receptacle is **always energized**
- One half is **automatically controlled**

This allows equipment requiring continuous power to remain energized while still complying with ARC requirements.

---

### Typical Implementation Methods

Common methods used in ARC implementations include:

- Split receptacles with a switched conductor
- Relay-controlled branch circuits
- Controlled receptacle circuits using lighting control relays
- Occupancy sensor–controlled branch circuits

---

### NEC Considerations

Relevant NEC considerations may include:

- Identification of controlled receptacles
- Branch circuit wiring methods
- Switching of grounded conductors (generally prohibited)
- Conductor identification and multiwire branch circuit considerations

Exact NEC sections vary by code edition and wiring method.

---

### Practical Implications

When ARC is implemented using switched receptacles:

- Electrical drawings must clearly identify **controlled receptacles**
- Contractors must correctly break the tab on split receptacles when required
- Controlled circuits must remain compliant with NEC switching rules

---

# 5. Common Interpretation Issues

### Controlled receptacle identification

Controlled receptacles must typically be **visually marked** to inform occupants that the outlet may turn off automatically.

---

### Continuous-load equipment

Equipment that must remain energized should not be connected to controlled receptacles.

Examples include:

- servers
- medical devices
- refrigeration equipment

---

### Partial control requirement

Energy codes typically require **only a portion of receptacles to be controlled**, not all receptacles.

Designers must ensure that:

- controlled outlets are clearly identified
- uncontrolled outlets remain available for continuous loads

